{
  "Question": "<p>For questions like \"What is the 1/2th root of x would the answer be <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_629\"><math alttext=\"x^{2}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></semantics></math></span>?</p> <p>My logic is that since <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_630\"><math alttext=\"\\sqrt[\\cfrac{1}{2}]{x}=x^{1/{(\\cfrac{1}{2}})}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mroot><mi>x</mi><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mroot><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>/</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></msup></mrow></semantics></math></span> Which simplifies to <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_631\"><math alttext=\"x^{2}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></semantics></math></span>.</p> <p>So as a general rule it could be <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_632\"><math alttext=\"\\sqrt[\\cfrac{1}{a}]{x}=x^{1/{(\\cfrac{1}{a}})}=x^{a}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mroot><mi>x</mi><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>a</mi></mfrac></mroot><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>/</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>a</mi></mfrac><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mi>a</mi></msup></mrow></semantics></math></span></p> <p>And with a different denominator <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_633\"><math alttext=\"\\sqrt[\\cfrac{b}{a}]{x}=x^{1/{(\\cfrac{b}{a}})}=x^{\\cfrac{a}{b}}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mroot><mi>x</mi><mfrac><mi>b</mi><mi>a</mi></mfrac></mroot><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>/</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mfrac><mi>b</mi><mi>a</mi></mfrac><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mfrac><mi>a</mi><mi>b</mi></mfrac></msup></mrow></semantics></math></span></p> <p>This corresponds to how decimal/fractional exponents denote radicals (their inverse) while fractional radicals are easier shown with exponents.</p> <p>Example : (2/3rd root of 4)</p> <p><span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_634\"><math alttext=\"\\sqrt[\\cfrac{2}{3}]{4}=4^{1/{(\\cfrac{2}{3}})}=4^{\\cfrac{3}{2}}=8\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mroot><mn>4</mn><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></mroot><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>4</mn><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>/</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>4</mn><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span></p> <p>Example (22/7th root of \u03c0) :</p> <p><span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_635\"><math alttext=\"\\sqrt[\\cfrac{22}{7}]{\u03c0}=\u03c0^{1/{(\\cfrac{22}{7}})}=\u03c0^{\\cfrac{7}{22}}\\approx 1.439\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mroot><mi>\u03c0</mi><mfrac><mn>22</mn><mn>7</mn></mfrac></mroot><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>\u03c0</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>/</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mfrac><mn>22</mn><mn>7</mn></mfrac><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>\u03c0</mi><mfrac><mn>7</mn><mn>22</mn></mfrac></msup><mo>\u2248</mo><mn>1.439</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span></p> <p>Example (1/2th root of 1/4) :</p> <p><span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_636\"><math alttext=\"\\sqrt[\\cfrac{1}{2}]{\\cfrac{1}{4}}=\\cfrac{1}{4}^{1/(\\cfrac{2}{1})}=\\cfrac{1}{4}% ^{(\\cfrac{2}{1})}=\\cfrac{1}{4}^{2}=\\cfrac{1}{16}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mroot><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mroot><mo>=</mo><msup><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>/</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mstyle scriptlevel=\"-1\"><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>1</mn></mfrac></mstyle><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mstyle scriptlevel=\"-1\"><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>1</mn></mfrac></mstyle><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>16</mn></mfrac></mrow></semantics></math></span></p>",
  "Title": "Can fractional/decimal radicals/roots exist?",
  "Tags": "radicals,decimal-expansion,radical-equations"
}